2026-06-24 | Rat Maze With Multiple Jumps

	Question
Return the path matrix, or [[-1]] if no path exists.
	Key Insight
This is a classic Backtracking problem.
At every cell:
		(i,j)
we can try:
		jump = 1
		jump = 2
		...
		jump = mat[i][j]
in increasing order.
Since the statement prefers:
		shorter jumps first
we iterate jump lengths from small to large.
For each jump:
		try right first
		then down
If a move leads to the destination, stop immediately.
	Approach
1.	Create answer matrix initialized with 0.
2.	Use DFS/Backtracking.
3.	Mark current cell as part of path.
4.	If destination reached:
			return true
5.	Try jumps:
			1 to mat[i][j]
6.	For each jump:
			right first
			then down
7.	If none succeeds:
			unmark current cell
			backtrack
8.	If no path exists:
			return [[-1]]
	Time Complexity
	Exponential in worst case
	Space Complexity
	O(n²)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    bool solve(int i,
               int j,
               vector<vector<int>>& mat,
               vector<vector<int>>& path,
               int n) {
        if(i == n - 1 && j == n - 1) {
            path[i][j] = 1;
            return true;
        }
        if(i < 0 || j < 0 ||
           i >= n || j >= n ||
           mat[i][j] == 0)
            return false;
        path[i][j] = 1;
        for(int jump = 1;
            jump <= mat[i][j];
            jump++) {
            if(j + jump < n &&
               solve(i,
                     j + jump,
                     mat,
                     path,
                     n))
                return true;
            if(i + jump < n &&
               solve(i + jump,
                     j,
                     mat,
                     path,
                     n))
                return true;
        }
        path[i][j] = 0;
        return false;
    }
    vector<vector<int>> ShortestDistance(
            vector<vector<int>>& mat) {
        int n = mat.size();
        if(mat[0][0] == 0)
            return {{-1}};
        vector<vector<int>> path(
            n,
            vector<int>(n, 0));
        if(solve(0, 0, mat, path, n))
            return path;
        return {{-1}};
    }
};
	Key Insight
The problem explicitly specifies the traversal priority:
		smaller jumps first
		right before down
